es and extends a tradition in which art exemplifies the understanding of existentialist philosophy. In a scholarly yet accessible style, the contributors exploit the rich interplay between Sartre’s philosophy, plays and novels, and a number of contemporary films including No Country for Old Men, Lost in Translation and The Truman Show, with film-makers including the Dardenne brothers, Michael Haneke, and Mike Leigh. This volume will be of interest to students who are coming to Sartre’s work for the first time and to those who would like to read films within an existentialist perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aExistentialism in motion pictures. 0aPhilosophy in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBoulé, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoulé, Jean-Pierre, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCooper, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarnell, Michelle R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalzon, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCaffrey, Enda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCaffrey, Enda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNicholls, Tracey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRolls, Alistair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanton, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoehr, Kevin L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul